        <p>Annual billing saves approximately 10–15%. A free trial is available.</p>

        <h2>What's actually included</h2>

        <p>Contractor Foreman packs a genuinely impressive feature list for the price:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Project management with Gantt scheduling</li>
          <li>Estimating and proposals with e-signature</li>
          <li>Job costing and budget tracking</li>
          <li>Time tracking with GPS verification</li>
          <li>Purchase orders and vendor management</li>
          <li>Client portal</li>
          <li>Subcontractor management</li>
          <li>Equipment tracking</li>
          <li>Daily logs and field notes</li>
          <li>Safety forms and checklists</li>
          <li>QuickBooks integration</li>
          <li>Lead and CRM management</li>
        </ul>

        <p>On paper, this matches or exceeds Buildertrend's feature set. In practice, the depth and polish of each feature varies.</p>

        <h2>Core features in detail</h2>

        <h3>Estimating</h3>
        <p>The estimating module lets you build proposals with line items, markup, and cost categories. Client-facing proposals look professional, include your branding, and support e-signature collection. Templates can be saved and reused for common job types. The workflow is functional and sufficient for most small contractors — not as elegant as JobTread's estimate-to-budget flow, but it works.</p>

        <h3>Project scheduling</h3>
        <p>Contractor Foreman includes a Gantt chart scheduler with task assignments and basic dependencies. Compared to Buildertrend's scheduling, it's simpler — the cascade logic when tasks are delayed requires more manual management. For straightforward project timelines, it's adequate; for complex multi-phase residential or commercial projects, you may find it limiting.</p>

        <h3>Job costing and budget tracking</h3>
        <p>Job costing is available on the Plus plan and above. You can track estimated vs. actual costs by category and see project profitability in real time. The implementation is functional, though the reporting interface is less intuitive than Buildertrend or JobTread.</p>

        <h3>Time tracking with GPS</h3>
        <p>Field crew time tracking with GPS verification is included on all plans. Workers clock in/out on mobile, with GPS coordinates recorded — useful for verifying that labor is being captured accurately and that hours are assigned to the right jobs. This feature works well and is comparable to dedicated time-tracking apps.</p>

        <h3>Client portal</h3>
        <p>A client-facing portal is available on Standard and above. Clients can view project progress, approve change orders, and pay invoices. Functionally it checks the boxes; the user experience is less polished than Buildertrend's portal, which matters if your clients are used to premium digital experiences.</p>

        <h3>QuickBooks integration</h3>
        <p>Connects to QuickBooks Desktop and Online. Invoices, expenses, and contacts sync between platforms. The integration is functional but has historically been less seamless than Buildertrend's — some users report needing to re-sync periodically. Check the current version's reviews on this specific point before committing.</p>

        <h2>What Contractor Foreman does well</h2>

        <h3>Price-to-feature ratio</h3>
        <p>No platform on the market delivers as many features per dollar. The Unlimited plan at $299/mo includes everything, for unlimited users. For a company with 10–20 team members, this beats Buildertrend's $499+/unlimited model even before accounting for feature depth differences.</p>

        <h3>Feature breadth</h3>
        <p>Equipment tracking, safety forms, purchase orders, subcontractor management, lead tracking — most competitors either skip some of these or put them behind higher tiers. Contractor Foreman includes them all, which matters for contractors who want a single platform instead of multiple tools stitched together.</p>

        <h3>Free trial</h3>
        <p>Unlike Buildertrend (demo only), Contractor Foreman offers a real free trial where you can use the platform before paying. This reduces the commitment risk significantly.</p>

        <h2>Where Contractor Foreman falls short</h2>

        <h3>User interface</h3>
        <p>This is the most consistent criticism from users who've tried both Contractor Foreman and competitors: the interface feels dated and cluttered. Navigation isn't always intuitive, and some workflows require more clicks than they should. New team members take longer to onboard than on JobTread or Buildertrend.</p>

        <h3>Customer support responsiveness</h3>
        <p>Multiple user reviews cite slow support response times, particularly on weekends and with complex issues. Buildertrend's support is notably better. If you're likely to need frequent help during implementation, this matters.</p>

        <h3>Scheduling sophistication</h3>
        <p>The Gantt scheduler exists but lacks the polish and dependency management of Buildertrend. If scheduling complexity is a primary pain point, this won't fully solve it.</p>

        <h3>Mobile experience</h3>
        <p>The mobile app covers the basics but isn't the standout experience that field teams expect from modern software. Time tracking works well on mobile; other features are less smooth.</p>

        <h2>Who should use Contractor Foreman</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Budget-conscious small contractors</strong> who need full PM features but can't justify $499/mo</li>
          <li><strong>Contractors coming off spreadsheets</strong> who need a significant feature upgrade without sticker shock</li>
          <li><strong>Teams with 5–20 users</strong> where per-seat pricing models elsewhere would add up quickly</li>
          <li><strong>Specialty trades</strong> that need equipment tracking and safety forms alongside standard PM</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who should look elsewhere</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Contractors where client-facing experience matters most</strong> → Buildertrend's portal is more polished</li>
          <li><strong>Teams prioritizing quick onboarding</strong> → JobTread is easier to learn</li>
          <li><strong>Businesses where support quality is critical</strong> → Buildertrend or JobTread have better support reputations</li>
          <li><strong>Commercial GCs needing enterprise compliance tools</strong> → Procore</li>
        </ul>

